[
    {
        "content": "<p>What's a good introduction to Grothendieck fibrations that explains the connection between <em>discrete</em> fibrations and functors <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>:</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">C</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow></msup><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F : \\mathsf{C}^{\\mathrm{op}} \\to \\mathsf{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">C</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">p</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span></span></span></span>?   I need one for my paper with <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276037\">@Jade Master</span>, <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276777\">@Mike Shulman</span> and <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276438\">@Fabrizio Genovese</span></p>",
        "id": 220747226,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1608680438
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't see anything at all about <em>discrete</em> fibrations in Borceux's book or Bart Jacobs' book, oddly enough.</p>\n<p>The <em>Elephant</em> talks about discrete fibrations but just <em>mentions</em> in passing that they're equivalent to presheaves; he doesn't prove it or even sketch why it's true.</p>",
        "id": 220747285,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1608680509
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276037\">@Jade Master</span> checked <em>Sheaves in Geometry and Logic</em> and couldn't find it there either. It was mentioned but nothing else.</p>",
        "id": 220747343,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1608680539
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>She didn't find it in Yau and Johnson's book on <em>Two-Dimensional Categories</em> either.</p>",
        "id": 220747375,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1608680569
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think Section 2.4 of Riehl's Category Theory in Context is good.</p>",
        "id": 220747567,
        "sender_full_name": "Christian Williams",
        "timestamp": 1608680720
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay, thanks - I'll check it out!</p>",
        "id": 220747742,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1608680864
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Alas, it doesn't say much about fibrations.  It has an exercise, 2.4viii, which defines \"discrete fibration\".  It tells you to show that given a presheaf on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>, the forgetful functor from its category of elements to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> is a discrete fibration.</p>",
        "id": 220747983,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1608681037
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So that's good, that's half the battle: the other half is taking a discrete fibration and getting a presheaf.  In the end you'd want to prove these two procedures give an equivalence of categories between presheaves on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> and discrete fibrations with base <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 220748034,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1608681111
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Loregian–Riehl's <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1806.06129\">Categorical notions of fibration</a> covers both the equivalence between discrete fibrations and presheaves, and the 2-equivalence in the non-discrete setting.</p>",
        "id": 220748544,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1608681501
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks, I'll look there.</p>",
        "id": 220748617,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1608681571
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yay, the thing I want is mentioned in the abstract, and it's Theorem 2.1.2., and it's actually <em>proved</em>.  <span aria-label=\"thumbs up\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f44d\" role=\"img\" title=\"thumbs up\">:thumbs_up:</span> </p>\n<p>Thanks!!!</p>",
        "id": 220748779,
